LinkNYC

In late 2015, New York City begun swapping payphones for kiosks called LinkNYC. These kiosks still have telephone access, but also have a tablet and wifi capabilities. According to NYC’s Open Data portal, there are 1,940 kiosks across the city. NYC also maintains a dataset of the status of each kiok’s status. On Canvas, there is a subset of these data called linknyc. Use these data for the following analysis.

Find the percent of kiosks with working phones, tablets, and wifi services by day. Plot these time series on the same set of axes. Make sure to color code the lines, label your axes, include a legend, etc. Describe what stands out to you in words (or econometric language).

nyc <- read.csv("../data/linknyc.csv")

# use lubridate functions to convert to day
# mdy_hms is for timestamps in that format, which this column is
# floor_date will round timestamps "down"
# this is super helpful for applied research!

nyc <- nyc %>%
  mutate(day = floor_date(mdy_hms(PUBLISH_DATE), "day"),
         wifi = ifelse(WIFI_STATUS == "up", 1, 0) * 100,
         tablet = ifelse(TABLET_STATUS == "up", 1, 0) * 100,
         phone = ifelse(PHONE_STATUS == "up", 1, 0) * 100) %>%
  group_by(day) %>%
  summarise(wifi = mean(wifi, na.rm = TRUE),
            tablet = mean(tablet, na.rm = TRUE),
            phone = mean(phone, na.rm = TRUE))

# Plot the data using ggplot2
ggplot(nyc, aes(x = day)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = wifi, color = "Wifi"), size = 1.5) +
  geom_line(aes(y = tablet, color = "Tablet"), size = 1.5) +
  geom_line(aes(y = phone, color = "Phone"), size = 1.5) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Wifi" = "tomato", "Tablet" = "mediumseagreen", "Phone" = "dodgerblue")) +
  labs(x = "Date", y = "Percent Working", color = "Device") +
  theme_minimal() +
  ylim(80, 95)

NYC Driver Applications

NYC’s Taxi and Limousine Commission (TLC) ingests many driver applications over time. Of course, not all applications are accepted. In Canvas, there is a file called nyc_driverapps. Use these data for the following analysis.

First, limit the data to only observations in 2017 or later. Next, find the number of applications that are accepted, and the number that are denied, by month. Plot these two time series on the same set of axes. Include a dashed vertical line for 3/11/2020. Make sure to color code the lines, label your axes, include a legend, etc. Describe what stands out to you in words (or econometric language).

Next, plot the fraction of applications that are accepted by month. Again, make sure to label, color code, etc. Speculate about the effect of the pandemic on driver applications.

# Read and process the data

nyc <- read_csv("../data/nyc_driverapps.csv") %>% 
  clean_names() %>%
  mutate(date = mdy(app_date),
         status_num = ifelse(grepl("Denied", status), 2, 1),
         month = floor_date(date, "month")) %>%
  filter(date > ymd("2017-01-01"))
## Rows: 154783 Columns: 12
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (11): Type, App Date, Status, FRU Interview Scheduled, Drug Test, WAV Co...
## dbl  (1): App No
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
# Aggregate data for plotting
plot_data <- nyc %>%
  group_by(month, status_num) %>%
  summarise(Freq = n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'month'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# First plot
ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = month, y = Freq, color = as.factor(status_num), group = status_num)) +
  geom_point(aes(fill = as.factor(status_num)), pch = 19, size = 2.5) +
  geom_line() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("1" = "black", "2" = "red"), 
                     name = "Status",
                     breaks = c("1", "2"),
                     labels = c("Accepted", "Denied")) +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = ymd("2020-03-15"), linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(title = "Driver Applications Over Time")

# Second plot
acceptance_rate <- plot_data %>%
  spread(status_num, Freq) %>%
  mutate(acceptance_rate = `1` / (`1` + `2`))

ggplot(acceptance_rate, aes(x = month, y = acceptance_rate)) +
  geom_point(color = "dodgerblue", pch = 19) +
  geom_line(color = "dodgerblue", type = "b") +
  theme_minimal() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = ymd("2020-03-11"), linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(title = "Fraction of Driver Applications Accepted Over Time", x = "Month", y = "Fraction Accepted")

SAT Scores

The SAT is a standardized test used widely by colleges and universities as admission criteria. The test’s scoring system has been revised a few times over the past 50 or so years. Dates of major changes are 1994 (+ calculators, - antonyms), 2005 (- analogies, + essay section, \(\Delta\) overall score) and 2016 (essay optional, \(\Delta\) # of multiple choice options, remove wrong-answer penalty, \(\Delta\) overall score).

In Canvas, there is a (messy) dataset called sat2.csv1. Clean these data to look more like the original source. Keep only rows with math scores (not 1941-1942 scale) and the first 7 columns. Name the columns something useful. Plot the total verbal and math scores over time with labels, colors, etc. Include vertical lines for each of the major SAT changes. What sticks out?

Second, make two plots side-by-side. In the first figure, plot all three math scores on the same set of axes. Make the scores-by-gender opaque2. In the next plot, do the same but use the verbal scores. Make sure the y-axis is the same on both figures. What do you notice?

Finally, plot the difference between the male and female math scores, and vertical lines for the changes in the SAT. Did any of the changes reduce the gap?

# Read the data
sat <- read.csv("../data/sat2.csv")

# Convert the text data to a proper dataframe
sat <- as.data.frame(matrix(sat$txt, ncol = 16, byrow = TRUE))
sat <- sat[sat$V2 != "---", 1:7]
colnames(sat) <- c("year", "verbal", "verbal_m", "verbal_f", "math", "math_m", "math_f")
sat <- sat %>% mutate(across(where(is.character), as.numeric))

# Main plot
ggplot(sat, aes(x = year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = verbal, color = "Verbal")) +
  geom_point(aes(y = verbal, color = "Verbal")) +
  geom_line(aes(y = math, color = "Math")) +
  geom_point(aes(y = math, color = "Math")) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(1994.5, 2005.5, 2016.5), linetype = "dotted") +
  labs(color = "Subject") +
    theme_minimal() +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Verbal" = "tomato", "Math" = "dodgerblue"))

# Split plots
sat %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -year, names_to = "subject", values_to = "score") %>%
  mutate(subject_type = ifelse(grepl("_m", subject), "Male",
                         ifelse(grepl("_f", subject), "Female", "Overall"))) %>%
  mutate(subject = ifelse(grepl("math", subject), "Math", "Verbal")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = year, y = score, color = subject_type, shape = subject_type)) +
  geom_line(aes(linetype = subject_type)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~ subject, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Overall" = "dodgerblue", "Female" = scales::alpha("tomato", 0.4), "Male" = scales::alpha("lightgreen", 0.7),
                     "Verbal" = "tomato")) +
      theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

ggplot(sat, aes(x = year, y = math_m - math_f)) +
  geom_line(color = "lightgreen") +
  geom_point(color = "lightgreen") +
  geom_vline(xintercept = c(1994.5, 2005.5, 2016.5), linetype = "dotted") +
        theme_minimal() +
  labs(y = "Math Score Gap")
